# Attachment & context discipline

When the user attaches a file larger than ~500 lines (or pastes a wall of code), follow these rules.

## Never re-read what is already in context

If the user already attached the file, do NOT call `Read` on the same file again. The bytes are already in your context. Use them directly. Calling `Read` on an attached file roughly doubles its token cost for no benefit.

## Read narrowly when you must read

When the user names a function, class, symbol, or line range inside a large file that is NOT already attached:

1. Use `Grep` (with the function/symbol as the pattern) to find the line numbers.
2. Use `Read` with `offset` and `limit` to load only ~30–80 lines around the match.
3. Do NOT read the entire file just to find one function.

For files known to be >1000 lines (e.g. `contract.service.ts`), this is mandatory, not optional.

## Quote code by reference, not by repetition

In your responses, NEVER paste back the entire attached file or large unchanged blocks of it. To point at existing code, use the code reference form `startLine:endLine:filepath` so the user sees a compact citation instead of a re-quote. Only show full code when proposing NEW or CHANGED code.

## Be surgical in edits

When fixing a bug in one function of a large service:

- Use `StrReplace` with the smallest unique snippet that disambiguates the location.
- Do NOT rewrite the entire file when only a function changed.
- Do NOT include adjacent untouched functions in the diff.

## Educate, but only once per session

If the user repeatedly attaches huge files for small surgical fixes, mention ONCE (not every turn) that they can narrow attachments with `@file#functionName` or `@file:startLine-endLine` in Cursor's prompt. After mentioning it once, stop bringing it up.

## Why this rule exists

Attaching a 1500-line service to ask about one function costs ~17K tokens per turn. Reading 50 lines around the function costs ~600 tokens. Same answer, ~30× cheaper. The rule exists to make the cheap path automatic and the expensive path deliberate.
